text.tspan: 6) To arrange necessary insurance for the vessel if required by the Owner.The Baltic and International Maritime Council (BIMCO), Standard Ship Management Agreement (SHIPMAN 98) form provides for thefollowing management services: crewing, technical management among a host of services. SHIPMAN 98 is also suitable formanagers supplying crew on a limited agency basis. For a more comprehensive and extensive crew management agreement, BIMCOhas created CREWMAN A, which is also on an agency or cost plus basis. For a manager supplying crew as principal or on a lumpsum basis, BIMCO has created CREWMAN B.If preferred by the owners, SHIPMAN 98 form shall be used to draw up the management contract by the Company.Company shall determine following in order to finalize the contractual terms1) Requirements specified by owners, including those for pre-delivery and post delivery (guarantee claims for new building, sale,recycling, scrap, etc.) activities,2) Requirements not stated by the owners, but necessary for specified and intended management services, where known as per priorexperience,3) Legal requirements as may be applicable to ship management services,4) Any additional requirements which may be required by the CompanyThe contract clauses may be modified and additional clauses may be incorporated in the SHIPMAN 98 form as per the aboverequirements and after mutual agreement with the owners.In order to fulfill the requirements of management services as specified in the management contract, the inputs relating to theserequirements shall be determined and records maintained. These inputs shall include:a) Vessel functional and performance requirementsb) applicable legal requirementsc) where applicable, information derived from previous similar designs, andd) other conditions for operation as considered acceptable3.4REVIEW AND VERIFICATION OF MANAGEMENT CONTRACTThe Managing Director shall be responsible for the review and verification of the management contracts and evidence that the termsof the management agreement have been approved shall be by means of the signed Contracts.Copies of the monthly operating and pre-operating cost budget shall be maintained in the vessel budget file and the vessel's initial andfollow-up inspection reports shall be stored in the concerned vessel's technical file.At the time of the vessel coming into the management a protocol of delivery and acceptance shall be signed, a copy of which shall beretained along with the signed copy of the management agreement for the vessel.Periodical account statements and technical reports as required by the owners shall be forwarded for their verification. The Director,Finance and the General Manager shall be responsible for their timely dispatch.Prior to the anniversary date of the agreement, a revised monthly operating cost budget for all the vessels shall be prepared andprojected to the owners for their review and mutual agreement. Copies of all these budgets shall also be filed for records.3.5BUDGET FOR SHIPSIn formulating a budget for a ship, the Technical, HSEQA, Accounts and Crew Departments play a collective role. After compiling, it isreviewed by the General Manager before projecting to the owners.Due consideration will be given to the minimum budget allocation for training and safety (Training - 3% to 4% of the OPEX and safety15% to 18% of the technical budget) depending on the specific requirements of each vessel.)3.6VESSEL PERSONNEL SERVICE CONTRACTPrior joining a vessel each officer and crew recruited is made to sign a Contract of Employment.3.7REVIEW OF CONTRACT OF EMPLOYMENT AND STANDARD TERMS AND CONDITIONSThe terms and service agreement of the officers are periodically reviewed by the Management keeping in mind the welfare of thepersonnel and at the same time to be competitive in the present day demand for experienced staff. Manning Offices and manningagents bring all such revisions to the notice of the vessel staff.3.8PLACING INSURANCE FOR THE SHIPMarine Superintendent or a responsible person nominated by General Manager, will place all necessary insurance policies as desiredby the Owners and simultaneously liaise with them in this respect.3.9EMPLOY AVERAGE ADJUSTERS, AGENTS ETCFor insurance claims involving various underwriters an average adjuster is nominated by the General Manager and appointed afterobtaining the consent of the owners.Normally Owner/ Charterers appointed agents are used for husbanding purposes. However when it necessitates appointing an agentin a port, the Technical Superintendent shall do it after making a cost study of Performa disbursement of various agents in that portand after having approval of the Owners.3.10CONTRACTS/ ENGAGEMENTS CONCERNING SALVAGEIn circumstances necessitating salvage assistance, the HSEQA Superintendent in consultation with the Managing Director/ GeneralManager will arrange for same with the salvage companies in the close vicinity and sign necessary contracts after obtaining consent
